When called with an empty string, {{bson_init_from_json()}} and {{bson_new_from_json()}} do not set {{error}} leaving it uninitialized which produces inconsistency with the documentation and requires an extra check to be made on the calling side.

Please refer to the following code snippet:

{code}
#include <stdio.h>
#include <bson.h>

int main() {
	bson_t bson;
	bson_error_t error;
	if (!bson_init_from_json(&bson, "", -1, &error)) {
		printf("bson_init_from_json() failed: %s\n", error.message);
		return 1;
	}
	bson_destroy(&bson);
	return 0;
}
{code}
{noformat}
$ ./a.out
bson_init_from_json() failed: �-T��
{noformat}

Introduced in CDRIVER-1692 circa commit [971af90ac2|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/commit/971af90ac2883690090f21ebd468904fdeae7b69]. Valid queries that mix $ and non-$ operators are prohibited, but they shouldn't be. An example of such a query is:
{code}
{"$or":[{"field1":1},{"field2":2}], "field3":3}
{code}
This results in cursor failure:
{code}
Cannot mix top-level query with dollar keys such as $orderby.
Use {$query: {},...} instead.
{code}

To illustrate the case, it is sufficient to pass an empty BSON as a command to {{mongoc_client_command_simple()}}:
{code}
src/mongoc/mongoc-cluster.c:183 mongoc_cluster_run_command_internal(): precondition failed: command_name
Aborted
{code}

When something is appended to the command, the issue is gone. See the example below:

{code}
#include <stdio.h>
#include <mongoc.h>

int main() {
	mongoc_client_t *client;
	bson_t command, reply;
	bson_error_t error;
	bool status;

	mongoc_init();

	client = mongoc_client_new("mongodb://127.0.0.1");
	BSON_ASSERT(client);
	bson_init(&command);
	
	// BSON_APPEND_BOOL(&command, "a", 1); // Issue is gone when uncommented

	status = mongoc_client_command_simple(client, "test", &command, 0, &reply, &error);
	if (!status) printf("Error: %s\n", error.message);

	bson_destroy(&command);
	bson_destroy(&reply);
	mongoc_client_destroy(client);
	mongoc_cleanup();
	return 0;
}
{code}

